{
  "Statistical results should always be interpreted:": "",
  "In the context of the study design, limitations, and real-world implications": "",
  "By ignoring effect sizes": "",
  "Only by looking at the p-value": "",
  "In isolation without considering context": "",
  "Context matters: the study design, potential biases, practical significance, and limitations all affect the interpretation of results.": "",
  "A statistically significant result does NOT necessarily mean:": "",
  "H0 was rejected": "",
  "The p-value is below alpha": "",
  "The effect is large or practically important": "",
  "The result is unlikely due to chance": "",
  "Statistical significance only means the effect is unlikely due to chance. With large samples, trivially small effects can be statistically significant.": "",
  "Correlation does NOT imply:": "",
  "A pattern in the data": "",
  "Causation": "",
  "Association between variables": "",
  "A linear relationship exists": "",
  "Two variables can be correlated without one causing the other. Confounding variables or coincidence may explain the association.": "",
  "When reading a research study, you should look for:": "",
  "Only the conclusion": "",
  "Sample size, study design, effect size, p-values, and potential biases": "",
  "The name of the journal only": "",
  "Only whether the result was significant": "",
  "A thorough evaluation requires examining all aspects of the study, not just whether the result crossed a significance threshold.": "",
  "Generalizability of results depends on:": "",
  "Only the sample size": "",
  "How representative the sample is of the population of interest": "",
  "The number of hypotheses tested": "",
  "Only the p-value": "",
  "Results can only be generalized to the population from which the sample was drawn. A biased or unrepresentative sample limits generalizability.": "",
  "A confidence interval that includes zero for a difference suggests:": "",
  "There is definitely no difference": "",
  "The difference is not statistically significant (zero is a plausible value)": "",
  "The study is invalid": "",
  "The sample size was too large": "",
  "If a CI for a difference includes zero, we cannot rule out the possibility of no difference, meaning the result is not statistically significant.": "",
  "Replication of results means:": "",
  "Copying data from another study": "",
  "Independent studies finding consistent results, increasing confidence in the findings": "",
  "Using the same sample twice": "",
  "Publishing the same paper in two journals": "",
  "When multiple independent studies reach similar conclusions, confidence in the findings increases substantially.": "",
  "The 'replication crisis' in science refers to:": "",
  "Too many studies being published": "",
  "A shortage of research funding": "",
  "Many published findings failing to replicate in independent studies": "",
  "Researchers copying each other's work": "",
  "The replication crisis refers to the finding that a substantial proportion of published research results cannot be reproduced, raising concerns about research practices.": "",
  "Effect size should be reported because:": "",
  "It is only important for small samples": "",
  "It replaces the need for hypothesis testing": "",
  "It is the same as the p-value": "",
  "It quantifies the magnitude of the effect, which p-values alone do not indicate": "",
  "Effect size tells you how large the difference or relationship is. A p-value only tells you whether the effect is likely real, not how big it is.": "",
  "Publication bias occurs when:": "",
  "Too many studies are replicated, leading to diminishing returns in new scientific knowledge": "",
  "Researchers only publish in top journals, limiting access for smaller research institutions": "",
  "All studies are published equally regardless of their results, leading to information overload": "",
  "Studies with significant results are more likely to be published than those with non-significant results": "",
  "Publication bias means the published literature overrepresents positive findings, giving a skewed view of what the full body of research actually shows.": "",
  "What does 'practical significance' mean?": "",
  "The study was conducted in practice rather than theory": "",
  "The effect is large enough to be meaningful or useful in real-world applications": "",
  "The sample is representative": "",
  "The p-value is below 0.05": "",
  "Practical significance considers whether the size of an effect matters in the real world. A treatment that improves outcomes by 0.1% may be statistically significant but practically meaningless.": "",
  "What does 'generalizability' mean?": "",
  "The number of variables in the study": "",
  "The extent to which study results can be applied to a broader population beyond the sample": "",
  "The strength of the correlation found": "",
  "The ability to calculate a p-value": "",
  "Generalizability (external validity) is the degree to which findings from a specific sample can be extended to the larger population of interest.": "",
  "What does 'effect size' mean?": "",
  "The width of the confidence interval used to estimate a population parameter": "",
  "The p-value of the test that determines whether the result is statistically significant": "",
  "The sample size of the study needed to achieve adequate statistical power for detection": "",
  "A standardized measure of the magnitude of a phenomenon or the difference between groups": "",
  "Effect size measures how big the observed effect is (e.g., Cohen's d, r, odds ratio), independent of sample size, helping assess whether the finding is meaningful.": "",
  "What is 'publication bias'?": "",
  "Bias introduced by the formatting of a paper": "",
  "The tendency to publish in only one journal": "",
  "A requirement that all studies must be published": "",
  "The tendency for journals to publish studies with significant results more often than those with null results": "",
  "Publication bias creates a distorted literature where positive findings are overrepresented, because null results are less likely to be submitted or accepted for publication.": "",
  "What does 'confounding' mean when interpreting results?": "",
  "A variable that has no effect on the results and can be safely ignored during the analysis phase": "",
  "The sample mean used as an unbiased estimator of the corresponding population parameter value": "",
  "A variable that improves the accuracy of the study by reducing random variation in measurements": "",
  "A third variable that is associated with both the explanatory and response variables, potentially causing a spurious association": "",
  "Confounding occurs when an unmeasured or uncontrolled variable explains the observed relationship, making it appear that one variable causes changes in another when it may not.": "",
  "What is 'Simpson's Paradox'?": "",
  "A statistical test that always gives paradoxical results": "",
  "An error in calculating the p-value": "",
  "A trend that appears in several different groups reverses or disappears when the groups are combined": "",
  "A type of sampling bias": "",
  "Simpson's Paradox occurs when a trend seen in subgroups reverses when data is aggregated, usually due to a lurking variable that changes the group compositions.": "",
  "What does 'external validity' mean?": "",
  "The p-value of the test": "",
  "Whether the study was conducted outside a laboratory": "",
  "The degree to which results can be generalized to other settings, populations, and times": "",
  "Whether external reviewers approved the study": "",
  "External validity concerns whether findings from one study context (specific sample, setting, time) apply to other contexts of interest.": "",
  "What does 'internal validity' mean?": "",
  "The degree to which the study design supports causal conclusions about the relationship between variables": "",
  "Whether the study was conducted inside a laboratory": "",
  "Whether the sample is large enough": "",
  "Whether internal reviewers approved the methodology": "",
  "Internal validity reflects how well a study can establish cause-and-effect relationships, primarily through controlling confounders and using randomization.": "",
  "What does 'meta-analysis' mean?": "",
  "A statistical technique that combines results from multiple studies to produce an overall estimate of an effect": "",
  "A method for calculating sample size needed before beginning a research study": "",
  "Analyzing metadata about a study such as its funding source and publication date": "",
  "Conducting a very large single study with thousands of participants across many sites": "",
  "Meta-analysis statistically combines data from many independent studies to obtain a more precise and reliable estimate of an effect than any single study can provide.": "",
  "What is 'cherry-picking' in the context of interpreting results?": "",
  "Selectively presenting only the results that support a preferred conclusion while ignoring contradictory evidence": "",
  "Choosing the largest study from a meta-analysis": "",
  "Selecting the best sample for analysis": "",
  "Picking the most appropriate statistical test": "",
  "Cherry-picking is the misleading practice of highlighting favorable evidence while omitting unfavorable evidence, creating a distorted picture of the research findings.": "",
  "A news article reports: 'Eating chocolate is linked to lower heart disease risk, according to a study of 10,000 adults.' The study is observational. A reader concludes that chocolate prevents heart disease. What is the flaw in this reasoning?": "",
  "The article correctly implies causation because the sample size of 10,000 is sufficiently large": "",
  "An observational study can show association but not causation; confounders like income or overall diet quality may explain the link": "",
  "The sample is too small to draw any conclusions about the relationship between chocolate and health": "",
  "Chocolate has no health properties, so the observed association must be due to measurement error": "",
  "Observational studies can identify associations but cannot establish causation. Wealthier people may eat more high-quality chocolate and also have better healthcare, creating a confounded association.": "",
  "A study finds that a tutoring program raises math scores by 2 points on a 100-point scale (p = 0.04, n = 5,000). The school board must decide whether to spend $500,000 implementing the program district-wide. What should they consider?": "",
  "The practical significance: a 2-point improvement may not justify $500,000, even though it is statistically significant": "",
  "Only the p-value, which shows the program works": "",
  "Nothing, because significant results always deserve funding": "",
  "The sample size alone": "",
  "While the effect is real (p = 0.04), a 2-point improvement on a 100-point scale is very small. The board should weigh whether this modest gain justifies the substantial cost.": "",
  "A university admission study finds that overall, male applicants have a higher acceptance rate than female applicants. However, within each individual department, female applicants have a higher acceptance rate. What statistical phenomenon explains this?": "",
  "The data was fabricated by university administrators to mask discriminatory admissions practices": "",
  "Type I error: the significant overall difference is a false positive caused by multiple testing": "",
  "The sample size was too small to detect meaningful differences in acceptance rates by gender": "",
  "Simpson's Paradox: women applied more to competitive departments with low overall acceptance rates": "",
  "This is a classic example of Simpson's Paradox (similar to the real Berkeley admissions case). Women applied disproportionately to more competitive departments, which reversed the trend when data was aggregated.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company publishes 3 studies showing their drug works (p < 0.05) but does not publish 7 other studies that found no significant effect. A doctor reads only the published studies and prescribes the drug. What problem does this illustrate?": "",
  "The studies were too small to provide reliable estimates of the drug's true effectiveness": "",
  "The 7 unpublished studies are irrelevant because only statistically significant results matter": "",
  "Publication bias: the doctor only sees the positive results, not the full picture of 3 out of 10 studies being significant": "",
  "The drug definitely works based on 3 positive studies since each met the significance threshold": "",
  "With 10 studies at alpha = 0.05, about 0.5 significant results would be expected by chance. Finding 3 out of 10 significant results, hidden by publication bias, may not actually demonstrate the drug works.": "",
  "Two studies on a weight loss supplement report different findings. Study A (n = 30): 'Participants lost 8 pounds (p = 0.15, not significant).' Study B (n = 3,000): 'Participants lost 0.5 pounds (p = 0.001, highly significant).' Which study found the more practically meaningful result?": "",
  "Both found equally meaningful results since each achieved statistical significance at alpha = 0.05": "",
  "Study B, because it is highly significant with a much smaller p-value and a larger sample size": "",
  "Study A found a larger effect (8 pounds vs. 0.5 pounds), but it was underpowered; the 0.5-pound loss in Study B, while statistically significant, is practically trivial": "",
  "Neither study is useful because weight loss supplement research is inherently unreliable overall": "",
  "Study A's 8-pound loss is practically meaningful but the small sample lacked power. Study B's 0.5-pound loss is real but trivial. This illustrates the difference between statistical and practical significance.": "",
  "A researcher studies whether caffeine improves reaction time. She finds r = 0.95 between coffee consumption and reaction speed in a sample of office workers. She concludes caffeine causes faster reactions. What is the primary flaw?": "",
  "Correlation does not imply causation; age, occupation, sleep habits, or other confounders could explain the association": "",
  "An r value of 0.95 is too strong to be real and likely indicates a calculation or data entry error": "",
  "Caffeine has no effect on the body, so the observed correlation must be entirely coincidental": "",
  "The sample of office workers is too small to detect any meaningful correlation between variables": "",
  "Even a very strong correlation (r = 0.95) in an observational study does not establish causation. Confounding variables may explain the relationship between coffee consumption and reaction time.": "",
  "A meta-analysis combines 50 studies on a dietary supplement and finds a small but significant benefit (pooled effect = 0.15 standard deviations, p < 0.001). However, a funnel plot suggests publication bias (small studies with negative results are underrepresented). How should this affect interpretation?": "",
  "The supplement should be immediately recommended to patients": "",
  "Funnel plots are irrelevant to meta-analyses": "",
  "Publication bias may inflate the pooled effect, so the true benefit may be smaller than 0.15 standard deviations or even zero": "",
  "The result is still reliable because the p-value is very small": "",
  "Publication bias means negative studies were likely not published, inflating the apparent effect. The true effect may be smaller or non-existent once missing studies are accounted for.": "",
  "A study reports a 95% CI for the difference in recovery times between two treatments as (-0.5 days, 3.2 days). What can you conclude about the difference?": "",
  "Treatment A is definitely better": "",
  "The difference is statistically significant because the CI is narrow": "",
  "The study was poorly designed": "",
  "The difference is not statistically significant because the CI includes zero, meaning no difference is plausible": "",
  "Since the confidence interval (-0.5, 3.2) contains zero, we cannot rule out that there is no difference between the treatments. The result is not statistically significant at the 5% level.": "",
  "A national study finds that students who take music lessons score 20 points higher on the SAT (p < 0.001). A school superintendent decides to require music lessons for all students to raise SAT scores. What is the main problem with this decision?": "",
  "The p-value is too small to be meaningful, indicating the result may be a statistical artifact": "",
  "The study is observational, so the higher scores may be due to confounders like socioeconomic status, not the music lessons themselves": "",
  "Music has nothing to do with academic performance so the superintendent should ignore the finding": "",
  "A 20-point improvement is too small an effect size to justify the cost of music lesson programs": "",
  "This is an observational study, so families who can afford music lessons may also provide other educational advantages. Requiring music lessons for all students may not reproduce the 20-point benefit.": "",
  "A researcher reports: 'Our study of 50 patients found no significant difference between the new drug and placebo (p = 0.12). We conclude the drug is ineffective.' A colleague argues this conclusion is too strong. Why might the colleague be right?": "",
  "Because placebos always work better than drugs when the sample size is below one hundred patients": "",
  "Because p = 0.12 mathematically proves the drug does not work and has zero therapeutic benefit": "",
  "Because 0.12 is very close to zero, suggesting the effect is essentially negligible in magnitude": "",
  "Because absence of evidence is not evidence of absence; the study with only 50 patients may have been underpowered to detect a real effect": "",
  "Failure to reject H0 does not prove the drug is ineffective. With only 50 patients, the study may lack sufficient power to detect a real but moderate effect. The correct conclusion is 'insufficient evidence,' not 'no effect.'": ""
}